entry.content:
# Steps to reproduce the problem
1. Create a Web Component with a shadow DOM :

Using nesting
```js
export default class Test extends HTMLElement {
  constructor() {
    super()
    const shadow = this.attachShadow({ mode: 'open' })
    shadow.innerHTML = `
      <style>
        :host {
          display: block;
        }

        :host::part(innerContent) {
          color: red;
        }

        :host {
          &::part(innerContent) {
            color: green;
          }
        }
      </style>
      <div>
        <p part="innerContent">I'm in the shadow DOM</p>
      </div>
    `
  }
}
```

2. Render those component

```html
<wc-nesting></wc-nesting>
<wc-media></wc-media>
```

3. display text should be green (it works fine with Firefox, but Safari fails)

# Problem Description
The use case for this is when we want to group style based on some attributes set on the :host

```css
:host {
  /* base style for :host */

  &::part(foo) { /* base style for foo */ }
  &::part(bar) { /* base style for bar */ }
}

:host([active]) {
  /* altered style for :host when active*/

  &::part(foo) { /* altered style for foo when :host is active */ }
  &::part(bar) { /* altered style for bar when :host is active */ }
}
```

This is a lot easier to read and manage.

# Summary
::part pseudo-element doesn't apply with nesting

